---
import Layout from '../../../components/layout/Layout.astro';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = 'Dispositivos para Ver Pasar el Tiempo';
---

<Layout
  lang={lang}
  title="Dispositivos para Ver Pasar el Tiempo — Work"
  description="Dispositivos para Ver Pasar el Tiempo (2020). Installation, sculpture. Devices for watching time pass. Maria Elvira Escallon."
>

  <article class="work-page">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="work-page__header">
        <p class="label">Work / 009</p>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="work-page__meta">2020 &nbsp;/&nbsp; Installation, sculpture &nbsp;/&nbsp; Variable dimensions</p>
      </header>

      <!-- Main gallery -->
      <div class="work-page__gallery">
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio:16/10;">[ Pending: Dispositivos para Ver Pasar el Tiempo — Overview of installation ]</div>
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio:16/10;">[ Pending: Dispositivos para Ver Pasar el Tiempo — Detail of sculptural device ]</div>
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio:16/10;">[ Pending: Dispositivos para Ver Pasar el Tiempo — Detail of temporal mechanism ]</div>
      </div>

      <!-- Text + Technical sheet -->
      <div class="work-page__body">
        <div class="work-page__text">

          <p class="curatorial">
            Is it possible to create a device to see time pass? This question articulates
            a series of pieces that seek to make the intangible tangible. The work proposes
            objects and mechanisms through which the passage of time — normally invisible,
            perceivable only through its effects — becomes something one can witness directly.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            Each device in the series approaches the problem from a different angle,
            using material processes — erosion, accumulation, dissolution, transformation —
            as instruments for rendering time visible. The pieces function not as clocks
            that measure time abstractly but as apparatuses that embody it materially,
            making duration something experienced rather than counted.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The title itself — <em>Devices for Watching Time Pass</em> — frames the work
            as both poetic proposition and technical challenge. Escallon's devices are not
            scientific instruments but sculptural ones, and their effectiveness lies not in
            precision but in presence: they ask the viewer to pause and witness processes
            that unfold at a pace radically different from the accelerated rhythms of
            contemporary life.
          </p>

          <h3 style="margin-top: var(--s4);">CONTEXT</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            Created in 2020, during a year of global pause and forced stillness, the work
            resonates with a collective experience of time distorted — stretched, compressed,
            made strange. The series extends Escallon's long engagement with temporality,
            connecting to earlier works like <em>In Memoriam</em> (ice dissolving over 20
            hours) and anticipating <em>Precipitacion de Arenas</em> (sand accumulating
            over the duration of an exhibition).
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="work-page__ficha">
          <h4>TECHNICAL SHEET</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <strong>Dispositivos para Ver Pasar el Tiempo</strong><br>
            2020<br><br>
            Installation, sculpture.<br><br>
            Variable dimensions
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">EXHIBITIONS</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            [ Pending exhibition data ]
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">HOW TO CITE</h4>
          <div class="ficha" style="font-size: 0.65rem;">
            Escallon, M.E. (2020). <em>Dispositivos para Ver Pasar el Tiempo</em>.
            Installation, sculpture. Available at:
            mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/dispositivos-para-ver-pasar-el-tiempo/
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>

<style>
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    }
</style>
